TELEGRAM TOPIC POLL — topic {{THREAD_ID}}, chat {{CHAT_ID}}, inbox {{INBOX}}, cwd {{CWD}}.
Session dir: /tmp/claude-telegram/sessions/{{THREAD_ID}}  (call it SESS below).
Bridge dir: ~/.telegram-bridge.

A. STATUS GAUGE (every tick, first):
   1. Read transcript_path from ~/.local/state/telegram-bridge/registry/{{THREAD_ID}}.json.
   2. If non-empty, run (ignore a non-zero exit = no usage yet):
        ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-context.py --transcript "<transcript_path>" --thread {{THREAD_ID}}
      This writes SESS/status.json; the router reads it to update the pinned sticky.

B. AUTO-COMPACTION CHECK (every tick, after status):
   1. Read trigger_pct from ~/.telegram-bridge/compaction.json (default 0.85).
   2. Read pct from SESS/status.json. If pct >= trigger_pct AND SESS/compacting.lock
      does NOT exist: run COMPACTION HANDOFF (below) and STOP this tick (don't also
      drain messages or run backoff).

C. DRAIN INBOX (every tick, unless a handoff just ran):
   Take a non-blocking per-topic lock so a replacement poller can't double-reply during
   a cutover — if you can't get it, another poller is active, so skip the rest of this tick.
   Use an atomic mkdir lock (portable across macOS + Linux; flock is NOT installed on
   macOS, so do not use it):
        mkdir SESS/poll.lock.d 2>/dev/null || (another poller active -> stop this tick)
   Hold the lock (the directory's existence) for steps 1-4; always rmdir it when done.
   1. Read read-offset from SESS/read.offset (default 0). Read {{INBOX}}; take lines after it.
   2. Record how many NEW lines there are as DRAINED (0 if none). If 0, skip to step 4
      (do NOT stop the tick — section D still runs so backoff can advance).
   3. For each new message line (JSON: text, message_id, optional image_path):
      a. image_path present -> Read that file first (screenshot/photo); text is the caption/instruction.
      b. else treat text as a task/question for THIS session.
      c. Process with full context, tools, memory.
      d. Reply: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "<your response>"
      e. BRIDGE COMMANDS — first token is one of these RESERVED names, leading "/" (preferred)
         or "!" (legacy), case-insensitive; strip the prefix before comparing:
           /status  -> reply with cwd + message count processed
           /context -> reply with the live context gauge: read SESS/status.json and report
                       pct, tokens, window, msgs (NON-destructive — just reports)
           /compact -> run COMPACTION HANDOFF (below) right now
           /dir <name|path> -> resolve against ~/.telegram-bridge/dir-aliases.json
                       (case-insensitive); else literal path (~ expanded). Note the change.
           /dirs    -> reply with the alias names from ~/.telegram-bridge/dir-aliases.json
           /end     -> Detach this session (transport teardown only): rm the registry
                       file, closeForumTopic, delete the poll cron (id in
                       SESS/poll.cron.id), reply "Session detached." If a
                       bridge-preamble asked you to preserve work first (e.g. journal +
                       checkpoint), honor that before tearing down.
         Only those SIX are bridge commands. Any OTHER "/" text (/track, /ship, /review, ...)
         is NOT a bridge command — treat it as a task so skills can be driven from the phone.
         (Daemon-level /new, /whoami, /sessions, /help never reach the inbox.)
   4. Write the new line count to SESS/read.offset. Release the lock: rmdir SESS/poll.lock.d.
   5. If DRAINED > 0, report briefly (e.g. "telegram: replied to 1 message").

D. BACKOFF RESCHEDULE (every tick, LAST — after A/B/C; skipped only when B handed off):
   Adaptive poll interval: fast (60s) while a conversation is active, ramping to a
   slow cap when idle, so the session does not burn context polling an empty inbox.
   State files in SESS:
     idle.count   — consecutive idle ticks (no message drained)
     poll.level   — current ladder index (0 = fastest)
     poll.cron.id — id of THIS poll cron (written at spawn; updated here on reschedule)
   Config (~/.telegram-bridge/compaction.json -> polling, read live):
     idle_intervals_seconds (default [60,120,300,1800] = 1m/2m/5m/30m) — the interval ladder
     ticks_per_rung         (default 3)                — idle ticks before advancing one rung
   1. If section C had DRAINED >= 1 this tick: write idle.count = 0 (active — snap back to fast).
      Else: idle.count = (current SESS/idle.count, default 0) + 1; write it.
   2. ladder = idle_intervals_seconds; n = len(ladder).
      target_level = min(idle.count // ticks_per_rung, n - 1).
   3. cur_level = SESS/poll.level (default 0). If target_level == cur_level: nothing to
      do — STOP the tick. (This is the common case: most ticks do not reschedule.)
   4. RESCHEDULE (the level changed):
      old_id = SESS/poll.cron.id (read it NOW, before overwriting).
      interval = ladder[target_level] seconds.
      cron expr: "* * * * *" if interval <= 60, else "*/<minutes> * * * *" where
        minutes = max(1, round(interval / 60)).
      a. Render the instantiated prompt for THIS session with the helper (it does the
         placeholder substitution from the raw template, so no literal braces ever
         appear in a live prompt):
           ~/.telegram-bridge/poll-render.sh {{THREAD_ID}} {{CHAT_ID}} {{INBOX}} {{CWD}}
         Capture its stdout — that is the prompt for the new cron.
      b. CronCreate(cron=<expr>, prompt=<substituted>, recurring=true, durable=false).
         Capture the NEW job id.
      c. Write new id -> SESS/poll.cron.id ; write target_level -> SESS/poll.level.
      d. CronDelete(old_id).  CREATE-BEFORE-DELETE: never a gap with no poller. The
         mkdir poll.lock.d guards the one-tick overlap from double-draining.
      e. Report: "telegram: backoff level <cur_level>->%<target_level> (<interval>s, idle <idle.count>)".

COMPACTION HANDOFF (run from B auto-trigger or the /compact command):
   You cannot shrink your own live context, so roll over to a FRESH replacement that
   restores saved state into the SAME topic. Steps, in order:
   1. Post: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "♻️ compacting — saving context and spawning a fresh session…"
   2. Produce a context handoff file at SESS/context-restore.md that the replacement
      can restore from. The default install uses the gstack /context-save skill: invoke
      it, capture the saved file path it prints, then `cp "<saved file path>"
      SESS/context-restore.md`. If you use a different save/restore mechanism, write its
      output to SESS/context-restore.md instead (see README "Customizing agent behavior").
   3. touch SESS/compacting.lock ; rm -f SESS/handoff-ready
   4. Spawn the replacement (attach mode). Attach intent is passed via FLAGS, not
      env vars, so it can't be inherited by a later manual spawn and hijack a live topic:
        bash ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-spawn.sh \
          --attach {{THREAD_ID}} --restore SESS/context-restore.md "{{CWD}}"
   5. Wait for SESS/handoff-ready to appear (the replacement writes it after restoring +
      attaching). Poll every few seconds up to ~5 min.
        - Not appearing in time: post "⚠️ compaction replacement didn't report ready; staying live.",
          rm SESS/compacting.lock, and ABORT the handoff (keep running normally).
   6. Hand off: CronDelete THIS session's poll cron (read the id from SESS/poll.cron.id),
      then rm SESS/compacting.lock (this releases the replacement to start its poll).
   7. Post: ~/.telegram-bridge/telegram-send.sh {{CHAT_ID}} {{THREAD_ID}} "✅ compacted — fresh session is live (was ~<pct>%)."
   8. Retire this tmux window for easy cleanup — ONLY if this session was itself spawned by
      the bridge (env TELEGRAM_BRIDGE_SPAWNED=1) AND $TMUX_PANE is set. Otherwise SKIP: an
      interactive session that merely bootstrapped the bridge must never retire itself.
      Target the window explicitly via $TMUX_PANE — a bare tmux rename-window /
      display-message resolves to the ACTIVE window, not this one, and would clobber the
      wrong window (e.g. the fresh replacement). Read kill_old from ~/.telegram-bridge/compaction.json:
        - kill_old false (default): rename so you can find it later:
            tmux rename-window -t "$TMUX_PANE" "DEAD - $(tmux display-message -t "$TMUX_PANE" -p '#W')"
        - kill_old true: kill this window (also ends this now-handed-off session):
            tmux kill-window -t "$TMUX_PANE"
   9. STOP. This session has handed off; take no further action.
